# Global Guidelines

## Git Commits

- Use short one-liner commit messages
- Always sign commits with -S flag
- Never add Co-Authored-By or AI attribution

## Pull Requests

- Never include "Generated with Claude Code" or similar AI attribution
- Never include Co-Authored-By lines
- Keep PR descriptions focused on the actual changes

## Code Style

- No unnecessary comments in code
- Prefer simple, readable solutions
- Follow existing patterns in the codebase
- No docstrings unless public API

## Changes

- Surgical: only change what's necessary
- Verify changes work before finishing
- Don't refactor unrelated code
- Don't add features beyond what was requested

## Don't Create

- README files unless asked
- Documentation files unless asked
- New abstractions for one-time use
- Backwards-compatibility shims

## Verification

- Run tests before considering work complete
- Build/compile to catch errors early
- Test the actual behavior, don't assume it works

## Security Reviews

Suggest running security-review agent after:
- Implementing authentication/authorization code
- Adding user input handling or form processing
- Working with database queries or external APIs
- Handling file uploads or path operations
- Adding cryptographic operations
- Before merging PRs with security-sensitive changes

## Stress Testing

Suggest running stress-test agent after:
- Implementing parsers or input handlers
- Writing memory-intensive operations
- Adding code that handles untrusted data
- Working with C/Rust unsafe code
- Before releases to find edge cases

## PR Workflow

- Use pr-review before merging non-trivial PRs
- Use pr-fixes to prepare branches for merge
- Run security-review on security-sensitive changes
- Run stress-test on code handling untrusted input
